  <div class= "caption">A S.A.F.E. kit. Photo courtesy of The Seattle Times.</div>

  <div class="headline">S.A.F.E. IN D.C.? the Accessibility of sexual Assault forensic services</div>
  <p class="chapter1">Part one: Some background</div>
  <div class="about">A sexual assault forensic exam is often referred to as a rape kit. The kit is just the container itself. It may hold any of the following:
<ul>Bags and paper sheets for evidence collection;</ul>
<ul>Comb;</ul>
<ul>Documentation forms;</ul>
<ul>Envelopes;</ul>
<ul>Instructions;</ul>
<ul>Materials for blood samples;</ul>
<ul>Swabs.</ul>
 A forensic exam is more detailed than your run-of-the-mill check up, and forensic nurses know to look for things others may miss. “Our nurse assess[es] anything that is an injury, pain, tenderness, and then documents it on a body map,” Colleen Gallopin of the District of Columbia Forensic Nurse Examiners explains. “We’ll do a pelvic exam. We’ll do photographs of any injuries, and then take down patient documentation of their report, as certain things are not photographable— pain, for example. Then, based on the patient’s account of what occurred, we will do the physical evidence collection, or the kit.” The exam alone could take upwards of four hours, and does not end when every stretch of skin has been seen. Body parts are swabbed, clothing is collected, and when appropriate, toxicology samples are taken. HIV testing, prophylaxis, and pregnancy prevention are also provided when necessary.</div>
<div id="hero"><img src="kitcontents.jpg" width= 900 height= 550 div class="hero-image">
<div class= "caption">The contents of a S.A.F.E. kit. Photo courtesy of TIME.
<div class="graphic-container">
<div class="graphic-headline">Of the eight emergency rooms that serve the D.C. public, only one — Medstar Washington Hospital Center — offers rape kit services.</div>

<div class="chapter2">Part two: what is the problem?</div> <br>

<div class="chaptertext">D.C. has a population of 700,000. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, this is the highest it has been since 1975. In the aftermath of a sexual assault, if a survivor requests a forensic exam, they can only have one perfromed at Medstar Washington Hospital Center. If they go to another emergency room in the city, they will likely have to travel by taxi or carsharing service to MWHC. During the busiest times of day, this can take more than an hour. United Medical Center, for example, is almost ten miles from MWHC.
Further, there are three hospitals in the city affiliated with universities. According to the AAU (American Association of Universities) Campus Climate Survey on Sexual Assault and Sexual Misconduct, and as reported by RAINN, "11.2% of all students experience rape or sexual assault through physical force, violence, or incapacitation (among all graduate and undergraduate students)."
<br>
<br>
<iframe src="https://uploads.knightlab.com/storymapjs/831fcb821b7c5619b0f9d2e266f65147/final-project-map/draft.html" frameborder="0" width="100%" height="800"></iframe>

<p class="chaptertext">Only a forensic nurse can conduct the exam. Forensic nurses complete extensive, specialized training before they can practice. In addition to a year of experience working in critical care, nurses complete 45 hours of classroom instruction and participate in a number of “hands-on” exercises.
When a patient presents at the Medstar ER seeking care after an assault, they can rely on being seen by a forensic nurse examiner after undergoing the initial emergency department triage. Medstar even has a separate, private room — complete with a door rather than a curtain — solely used for this purpose. The program at Medstar Washington Hospital Center is a partnership between the hospital and the non-profit organization, District of Columbia Forensic Nurse Examiners. But, since it is the sole program in the city, why don’t other area hospitals just train and keep their own SANE nurses on hand? It seems like a simple solution, but a few factors prevent this.

<br>

