<div class="chapter3">Part three: what can be done?</div> <br>
  <p class="graphic-text">As one might expect, there is no direct answer to this problem.Funding, naturally, plays a role. A representative from GW Hospital explained The Office of Victims Services within The District’s Mayor’s office is funded by the Department of Justice. In 2008, when the city’s SANE program was reestablished, it opened funding requests for non-profit 501©3 organizations. GW is not a non-profit hospital, so did not meet applicant qualifications. GW will not turn an assault survivor away; they will triage and treat any individual who comes to the emergency room. But, if a patient wants a forensic exam, “GW can and has requested that the SANE nurse from MedStar Washington Hospital Center come to GW and collect evidence,” Susan Griffiths, the Assistant Director of Marketing at George Washington University Hospital said.


    <div class="hero" width= 550><img src="askdc.png" width= 550 height= auto div class="photos">
    <p class= "caption"></p></div>

<p class="chaptertext">DC is, as it turns out, not the only city to approach the situation this way. Kim Day, an RN and the Forensic Nursing Director with the International Association of Forensic Nurses, notes Baltimore used to have only one Forensic Nursing program at Mercy Hospital. Though the Greater Baltimore Medical Center also has a program now, Mercy, like Medstar Washington Hospital Center, will send a forensic nurse to a patient at other hospitals if the patient is unable to be moved. Dallas, Day notes, is an example of a city that has more than one program. But, the city only began employing forensic nurses in the past decade.

Accessibility, though, remains a major concern for Gallopin.

She hopes in the future the partnership between Medstar and DC Sexual Assault Nurse Examiners will continue to strengthen, and the process patients must go through to obtain care will become more smooth. Shortened wait times and streamlining referrals from other hospitals are focus areas for improvement. Providing services in non-hospital settings (like community health clinics), and expanding outreach to the area’s more marginalized populations are also goals.

Above all, DC Forensic Nurse Examiners hopes to increase the public’s knowledge of the work they do: “No matter who survivor turns to first, that individual knows to turn to us.”

<br></p>

